PROJECT 2: AWS Threat Detection Lab
Date: Day 5
What I built:

Enabled GuardDuty (24/7 threat detection)
Generated and analyzed sample security findings
Enabled Security Hub with AWS Foundational Security Best Practices and CIS AWS Foundations Benchmark
Created CloudTrail trail with permanent S3 storage, CloudWatch Logs and Log File Validation enabled
Created SNS topic with confirmed email subscription for real time alerts
Connected GuardDuty to EventBridge to SNS for automatic email notification when threat is detected

Security concepts applied:

Continuous threat monitoring (GuardDuty)
Centralized security management (Security Hub)
CIS benchmark compliance checking
Audit logging with long term retention (CloudTrail)
Log File Validation to prevent log tampering
Automated incident alerting (EventBridge + SNS)
Least privilege with dedicated IAM roles per service

Challenges faced and resolved:

AWS account showing incomplete registration — resolved by enabling IAM billing access from root account
GuardDuty not accessible initially — resolved after account was fully activated
Received unexpected account upgrade email — investigated and confirmed account remains on Basic Support plan with zero charges

Real world value:

This exact setup is used by companies paying thousands of dollars per month for security monitoring
Built completely for free using AWS Free Tier
GuardDuty, Security Hub and CloudTrail is the standard AWS security stack asked about in every cloud security interview

